From: Abhinav Ayyapasetti <ayyapasetti.abhinav@windriver.com>
Date: Tue, 10 Mar 2026 07:39:14 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] mgr/rbd_support: Use monotonic clock for Throttle timing

Replace datetime-based timing with time.monotonic() for more reliable
throttling that is not affected by system clock changes.

The Throttle decorator protects against rapid consecutive calls to
trash image removal progress monitoring. Using datetime.now() can
cause issues when system clock changes, and the comparison with
datetime.min can lead to segmentation faults in certain scenarios.

time.monotonic() provides a monotonic clock that only moves forward
and is not affected by system time adjustments, making it more
suitable for measuring elapsed time intervals.

Signed-off-by: Abhinav Ayyapasetti <ayyapasetti.abhinav@windriver.com>
---
 src/pybind/mgr/rbd_support/module.py | 6 +++---
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/pybind/mgr/rbd_support/module.py b/src/pybind/mgr/rbd_support/module.py
index f878933..398788d 100644
--- a/src/pybind/mgr/rbd_support/module.py
+++ b/src/pybind/mgr/rbd_support/module.py
@@ -537,13 +537,13 @@ class PerfHandler:
 
 class Throttle:
     def __init__(self, throttle_period):
-        self.throttle_period = throttle_period
-        self.time_of_last_call = datetime.min
+        self.throttle_period = throttle_period.total_seconds()
+        self.time_of_last_call = 0
 
     def __call__(self, fn):
         @wraps(fn)
         def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
-            now = datetime.now()
+            now = time.monotonic()
             if self.time_of_last_call + self.throttle_period <= now:
                 self.time_of_last_call = now
                 return fn(*args, **kwargs)
